<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:g-custom="http://base.google.com/cns/1.0" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/">
  <title>Racism in South Africa</title>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.themarketintellect.co.za" />
  <subtitle>After all these years, since the fall of Apartheid, South Africa is still struggling with racism. Who is now holding the short end of the stick?</subtitle>
  <entry>
    <title>Racism in South Africa</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.themarketintellect.co.za/racism-in-south-africa" />
    <author>
      <name />
    </author>
    <updated>2020-09-15T16:33:50Z</updated>
    <published>2020-09-15T16:33:50Z</published>
    <content>&lt;h3 style="transition: opacity 1s ease-in-out 0s;"&gt;&#xD;
  
                  
         The South Africa promised by political leaders at the 1994 democratic election, has not materialised. After 26 years the majority in South Africa still suffers, probably more than during the apartheid era, from the same issues, and “democracy” has brought little relief to the majority. 
        
                &#xD;
&lt;/h3&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;img src="https://irp-cdn.multiscreensite.com/a81d873f/dms3rep/multi/ALM.png"/&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;h3 style="transition: opacity 1s ease-in-out 0s;"&gt;&#xD;
  
                  
         HOW ARE BLACK PEOPLE BEING TREATED IN SOUTH AFRICA?
        
                &#xD;
&lt;/h3&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div style="transition: none 0s ease 0s; display: block;" data-rss-type="text"&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 22px;"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           The following quote in The New York times says it all: 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;i style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           “In the history of civil rights, South Africa lays claim to a momentous achievement — the demolition of apartheid and the construction of a democracy. But for black South Africans, who account for 75% of this nation of roughly 55 million people, political liberation has yet to translate into broad material gains.” (P.S. Goodman, The New York Times, 24/10/2017)
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/i&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;i style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;/i&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          It is then no wonder that M. Mduli of News24, 14/09/2020 states that B-BBEE has not delivered meaningful empowerment, even in business. Instead of fixing the damage, racial inequality has been on the rise, making South Africa the most unequal country in the world. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           In the top ten South African (JSE) companies 68% of directors of the top companies still are still males. White people are still dominant at 72%.
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          (Sources, websites of the top 40 companies on JSE &amp;amp; M. Nyirenda, University of Pretoria, Nov. 2010, “Board composition in companies listed on Johannesburg Securities exchange.”)
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          If the black people are still worse of than before, then why must other race groups suffer because of B-BBEE and preferential treatment for "previously disadvantaged people" because it clearly doesn't work. The futile attempt by the authorities only causes racial tension between groups.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Despite the promises made to the South Africans population, unemployment numbers have grown from 1994 to 2014 by 71%. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           The unemployment rate is at a record level of 30,1% in 2020 (before Covid-19).
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The number of unemployed black people has increased during the 20-year period of democracy by 3,2m or by 79%. Almost 60% of unemployed people in South Africa are black after 20 years since 1994.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          16 Years after the end of apartheid (2010) black people are still part of the lowest income group in South Africa. A black person earned R10,000-00 per year, whilst a white person still earned 8 times more at R79,500-00 per year. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The ratio between black and white pay is 1: 7,95. The situation has worsened by 2015 at B: W = 1: 8,42. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          After 21 years of democracy, the black population is still the lowest paid race group in South Africa.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Why is this so after 21 years since democracy? 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The number of people living in slums in South Africa has increased by 1,8m over the past 10 years.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          18 million people are dependent on social grants. This is 32% of the total population. This number has increased from 5,8 million in 2003 to 18 million in 2020.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The number of people in jobs in 2020 is 16,38 million. This means that there are fewer people earning in South Africa than those depending on grants. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           There still are numerous statistics showing that the trillions of ZAR spent to uplift the black South Africans, had very little effect on a macro/national basis. Where has the money been spent? 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          THE ORIGIN OF RACISM.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          It is claimed by some researchers that racism is by instinct, however, it has already been scientifically been proven that this is incorrect. Racism is something that has developed over time, and is not present from birth.  
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           In South Africa it is possible that that frustration could be leading to aggression against a minority group. This will happen if the state does not remove inequalities fast enough. The question is: has this aggression already started in South Africa?
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The lack of corrective action and hence poverty for a race group could lead to the privileged group seeing itself as superior to the disadvantaged group. This could lead to aggression by the disadvantaged group. A study has revealed in 1985 that the relationship between black and white people in South Africa is poor due to exactly this. Has this changed after 26 years of democracy? 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The effect of previous conflict between groups can last for generations. The historical conflicts between Boer (white) and black people has an impact on relations between black and white, which has spread into society. This has also led to distrust between the community and the police. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           A deterioration of socio-economic conditions of a group will lead to a perception of a lower status of that group. As previously discussed, the socio-economical position of black people in South Africa is still dire, and hence it is possible that the rest of the country could view them as lower status citizens.
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Then there are the factors that increases group norms:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Racial discrimination frequently in the news.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	A group perceives itself as above the other group(s).
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The role of parents.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Massmedia.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The members of one group is expected of to maintain a negative view of other group(s).
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Groups isolate themselves from other groups.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;b&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           SUMMARY:
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/b&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Factors increasing the probability of racism:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           -	The role of parents!
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The violent protests by black people are creating a negative perception at other groups and stakeholders.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The current weak economy is also creating negative attitudes between groups, eg. B-BEE is creating expectations and disappointments (see Mduli above).
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Authoritarian personalities and leaders. Is racism part of THE STRUGGLE, or is the national drive to make it better for all? Is it acceptable that the state views itself as a struggle movement?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Needs not satisfied will upset groups. It became evident during the Covid-19 pandemic that the needs of South African people are definitely not met.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Continuation of racial negative perception after attempts to eliminate it. Is the South African state honestly attempting to eliminate racial perceptions, or is it using racism to gain votes?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The maintaining of group norms in the different race groups supports racial perceptions.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Differences of religions.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Race biological differences.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Social and economic differences.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Previous wars.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Number of members represented by groups.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Work reservation. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;b&gt;&#xD;
      &lt;i style=""&gt;&#xD;
        
                        
            IT MUST BE POINTED OUT THAT THE RACIAL PROBLEM CAN BE SOLVED IN SOUTH AFRICA.      
           
                      &#xD;
      &lt;/i&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;/b&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;</content>
    <summary type="text" />
    <g-custom:tags type="string">#AllLivesMatter</g-custom:tags>
    <media:content medium="image" url="https://irp-cdn.multiscreensite.com/a81d873f/dms3rep/multi/ALM.png" />
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <title>CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR AFTER LOCKDOWN LEVEL 5 AND 4.</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.themarketintellect.co.za/consumer-behaviour-after-lockdown-level-5-and-4" />
    <author>
      <name />
    </author>
    <updated>2020-07-01T11:25:10Z</updated>
    <published>2020-07-01T11:25:10Z</published>
    <content>&lt;h3 style="transition: opacity 1s ease-in-out 0s;"&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           BUSINESSES MUST BE AWARE OF THE CHANGES THAT ARE HAPPENING, OR HAVE HAPPENED NOW. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          ARE YOU READY TO BE A “LONG-LIFE” SUPPLIER OF GOODS OR SERVICES?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          HOW SUSTAINABLE IS YOUR BUSINESS IN THE POST-COVID-19?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          INNOVATION WILL BE THE SOURCE OF FUTURE GROWTH. (A good example is where one could install software that would protect consumers against infection via food.)
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/h3&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;img src="https://irp-cdn.multiscreensite.com/md/unsplash/dms3rep/multi/photo-1586778330674-dbb744a1d98c.jpg"/&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div style="transition: none 0s ease 0s; display: block;" data-rss-type="text"&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           Panic buying is happening without any significant signs to the general public. Is it happening without people realising that it has become a reality, or that is the new way of buying?    
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Consumer behaviour has changed because of panic buying. The buying pattern is almost the same as just before the 1994 elections. The only difference now is that panic buying occurs now more regularly than in 1994. It is speculated that the current regular panic buying is caused by a low trust level in the unilateral decisions made by the government.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Uncertainty is causing consumers to stock up. These uncertainties are driven by unfamiliarity with court decisions, the tobacco debacle, conflicting news re infection and death numbers, people defying regulations as regulations now is seen to be targeting a small part of the population (who is staying at home now?). The current taxi debacle is not doing any good. The Minister of Transport who is blatantly ignoring the powerful taxi industry by not attending/delaying meetings with the taxi leaders. Retaliation by taxis was to fill up taxis to at least 100%. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           Even border control is suspect. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           The question is, do we still have any lockdown that will prevent the spreading of the Covid-19?
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The harsh treatment of the public by the police and SANDF and subsequent outcomes of investigations also do not create an atmosphere of trust. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           The rumours about Eskom and diesel shortages make consumers and the public uncertain of what the “real” status is in South Africa. The fact that samples for the Corona virus has a big backlog for testing, samples are thrown away (e.g. thousands of samples have been found thrown away next to a road in the Eastern Cape) also confuses the public and that have led to erratic consumer and public behaviour. 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Above uncertainties worries consumers and lead to sporadic panic buying. Suppliers like the dairy industry are actually experiencing an increase in sales of long-life products. This increase is currently leading to shortages in supply to the end user.  
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          BUSINESSES MUST BECOME “LONG-LIFE” SUPPLIERS.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          FOCUS ON SUSTAINABILITY.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;</content>
    <summary type="text" />
    <g-custom:tags type="string" />
    <media:content medium="image" url="https://irp-cdn.multiscreensite.com/md/unsplash/dms3rep/multi/photo-1586778330674-dbb744a1d98c.jpg" />
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <title>EXAMPLES OF CREATIVENESS AS WELL AS PRO-ACTIVITY OF POST-LOCKDOWN/POST-VIRUS.</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.themarketintellect.co.za/examples-of-creativeness-as-well-as-pro-activity-of-post-lockdown-post-virus" />
    <author>
      <name />
    </author>
    <updated>2020-04-29T06:21:51Z</updated>
    <published>2020-04-29T06:21:51Z</published>
    <content>&lt;h3 style="transition: opacity 1s ease-in-out 0s;"&gt;&#xD;
  
                  
         BUSINESS HAS CHANGED FOREVER IN SOUTH AFRICA, ESPECIALLY WITHIN A RECESSION. THE OLD SAYING OF “ADAPT FOR SURVIVAL” IS SO VERY TRUE. “BUSINESS AS USUAL IS FOREVER GONE”.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          THE MARKET INTELLECT HEREBY WANTS TO ATTEMPT TO “MAKE BUSINESSES HAVE ANOTHER URGENT RELOOK” AT THEIR STRATEGY, MISSION, SALES, MARKETING, MARKET INTELLIGENCE TOOLS, ETC. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/h3&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;img src="https://irp-cdn.multiscreensite.com/md/unsplash/dms3rep/multi/photo-1498811008858-d95a730b2ffc.jpg"/&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div style="transition: none 0s ease 0s; display: block;" data-rss-type="text"&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;b style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           1.	RETAILER SALES.
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/b&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Retailers have reported a sharp drop in sales. They must re-invent their way of doing business. Here are a few examples of adaptation for survival:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Launch your own on line delivery boxes as “self-isolation packs”.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Increase focus on shelf stable products, i.e. pantry product type sales. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Deliveries direct to customers/consumers via e-commerce platforms, home delivery. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	What about quarantine centres?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Cater for increasing “at-home channels” at the expense of “away-from-home”. Attempt to grow in this context via e-commerce.  
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Adapt to the behavior change to growing own food, e.g. vegetables, fruit, yogurt, etc.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Utilise the vast amount of data regarding individuals to sharpen up on the customer/consumer in-home, preferably via e-commerce. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Be careful with new product launches. It could be different to what was planned.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Develop sustainable food systems.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Use R&amp;amp;D companies to develop new products on real time. Look for real-time, high resolution, live streaming of product trials (Tetra Pak).
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Be aware that many suppliers have moved out of the supply chain as the lockdown has forced the suppliers to close.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	What about paid residential deliveries by drone?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Take note of the Nielsen report stating that “pantries are padded with produce as consumers prepare for the long wait caused by Covid-19.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;b&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           2.	SOME OTHER ADAPTATIONS FOR SURVIVAL.
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/b&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	There are hundreds (if not thousands) of businesses that want to move on line.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Could your business survive by adapting a day-by-day, week-by-week, month-by- month way of doing business?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	What about engaging with health-focused audiences?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Build an image of cleanliness to a level that creates confidence and a feeling of safeness.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Clean Hotels, guesthouses, etc. must accept that the majority of meals will probably only be done via room service.  
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Take note that there is a shift to indulgence among consumers.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Try to land agreements with government to supply health related goods.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Realise that people will be hesitant to go to the supplier/service provider and will prefer to do business on line or via e-commerce. Also re-invent to collect from customers.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          REFERENCES:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
