  </entry>
  <entry>
    <title>WHAT WILL AN “AFTER THE VIRUS” ECONOMY LOOK LIKE?</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.themarketintellect.co.za/what-will-an-after-the-virus-economy-look-like" />
    <author>
      <name />
    </author>
    <updated>2020-04-13T12:46:37Z</updated>
    <published>2020-04-13T12:46:37Z</published>
    <content>&lt;h3 style="transition: opacity 1s ease-in-out 0s;"&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           WHAT WILL THE CHANGE OF THE RSA ECONOMY BE? 
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          IT WILL PROBABLY TAKE ON A CHANGE FROM THE VUM SCENARIOS OR A MIX THEREOF. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          WILL THE PRESIDENT BE THE SAME KIND OF TOP LEADER AS HE WAS DURING THE LOCKDOWN DECISIONS AND PERIODS? 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          WILL THE COVID-19 BE USED AS AN EXCUSE TO FURTHER, AND EXPAND THE NATIONAL DEMOCRATIC REVOLUTION (“NDR”)? 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          THERE ARE 1.6 MILLION INFECTIONS, 430,000 HAVE RECOVERED AND 120,000 HAVE DIED, WHAT ABOUT THE REMAINING 1 MILLION, ARE THEY STILL INFECTED?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/h3&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;a&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;img src="https://irp-cdn.multiscreensite.com/a81d873f/dms3rep/multi/south-african-money-1573874-1280x960-78dc294e.jpg" alt=""/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/a&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div style="transition: none 0s ease 0s; display: block;" data-rss-type="text"&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;span style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"&gt;&#xD;
      
                      
           1.	PREAMBLE.
          
                    &#xD;
    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Experts are of the opinion that the COVID-19 infections will stop, once the Virus runs out of people to infect!
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The RSA economy has come to a halt due to travel bans, lockdowns, low oil prices, global economic slowdown, and the recession prior to the “Virus”.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The RSA economy is in distress. What now?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The BER (06/04/20, Report 13) describes the RSA economy as having a “triple sudden stop”, which are:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	A sharp decline in global demand for our exports.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The lockdown leading to a sharp drop in domestic production and demand.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	A combination of the two.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          P.	Cairns (09/04/20, “Three scenarios for a recovery) is concerned that the RSA is able to handle the crisis:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Oil price war.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	 The weak ZAR.  
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Mike Schussler (KYKNET VERSLAG, 09/04/20) estimate the probable job losses due to the Virus lockdown and the extension of the lockdown to be approximately 3 million.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          I CANNOT UNDERSTAND HOW ONE OF MY CHINESE CLIENTS ARE OFFERING BOXES OF COVID-19 TEST KITS, 114/BOX AT  USD 92/BOX BUT WE HAVE NOT ENOUGH KITS TO TEST?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          SARS has missed their collection revenue by R66 Billion. Add to this that we were in a recession before the Virus, and then the situation will look dire. Also adding the senseless decision to ban alcohol and cigarette sales will do us economic harm, and will really cost the government image somewhat.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          We do not need all of this, keeping in mind the S&amp;amp;P evaluation of the government credit rating in May 2020 (next month).  
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          2.	AFTER.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          South Africa will enter the post-Virus era with a heavy burden which already exists:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The PMI’s have plummeted to record lows.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Eskom sales are down by at least 9,500 MW.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	New vehicle sales are the lowest in more than a decade.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The ZAR has lost +30% against the USD and, important to note, 22% against the Chinese Yuan.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Downgrades by Moody’s and Fitches (remember S&amp;amp;P in May 20).
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Land grabbing has flared up.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Looting of stores has increased.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	55 Schools have been burnt or vandalised.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	There are daily traffic jams in cities (contempt for state, or unorganised?).
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Will the economy be able to recover?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          ON THE OPTIMISTIC/POSITIVE SIDE:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The curve of COVID-19 infections has already levelled out.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Informal traders have been permitted trade again.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The Chinese PMI has improved significantly which will start the agonising global return to business.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The ZAR will eventually strengthen, albeit slower than after the economic collapses of the past. The credit ratings will dampen strengthening of the ZAR. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	There is a common sense of purpose developing in communities, e.g. gangs in the Cape Flats have decided to stop turf wars and to join hands in distributing food parcels.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          3.	UNFAIRNESS.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          First of all, there must be reference to B. Curson (09/04/20, “Big businesses left out in the cold”, Moneyweb web site) stating that there is NO TAX relief for large businesses. This despite the fact that these businesses are important in creating and providing employment, paying Vat, PAYE, excise duties, provisional taxes, and many, many more to support the economy.  On top of all this, there is low (or no) demand for non-essential goods or services which will create cash flow problems.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          “SARS appears to have a ‘Hard line’ to large employers during the COVID-19 pandemic.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Also, not that additional to the mentioned hardship large factories and deep mines will take a long time to start up and run at normal levels.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          To add salt to the wounds, it must be noted that the leader of the FF+, Pieter Groenewald (KykNet News, 09/04/20), has objected to the state financially support only BEE businesses, thus the state ignoring the non-BEE businesses, regardless of SMME status. It seems also that the FF+ contributions to the Solidarity Fund will not happen out of protest.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          4.	PLEASE LET US GO BACK TO NORMAL. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The probability that the RSA will go back to normal is low, if not = 0. Above problems, questions and concerns almost guarantee a new business era in the RSA. Business must have their plan B to G ready and in place.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          C. Pedersen &amp;amp; T. Ritter (HBR, 10/04/20) list a few concerns that business should take serious after lockdown:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          - A collapse of customer demand.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          - Emergency regulatory measures by the state remains in place.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          - Supply chain interruptions.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          - Unemployment extremely high.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          - The economic recession gets worse.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          - Increased uncertainty by all, including business, environment, people.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          5. RECOVERY.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The monkey is on the back of the private sector. Government does not have the resources to improve the economic environment.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          S. Khumalo (Fin24, 10/04/2020, “Open fast food retailers say business chamber as Ramaphosa extends lockdown.”) reports on the lockdown and its extension. The argument by the Business Chamber is that fast foods already operate under strict hygiene and safety standards, and that they hence qualify to do business.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          He also advocates a staggered approach to kick start the RSA economy.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          The result here is that food companies should also trade, which is great. The optimistic spin-off is that all businesses that are accredited according to specific QA systems may then also trade.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Above is also in line with what Wall Street is expecting and planning: 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	The economy to be re-opened in phases.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	This re-opening will start in smaller cities, and towns, that were not severely hit by the Virus. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          Some of the questions that needs to be asked by business:
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Can you regain lost ground?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Re-visit your business plans and strategy.
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Can you culturally deal with the crisis and the aftermath?
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div style="text-align: justify;"&gt;&#xD;
    
                    
          -	Look again at projects, renewing, re-inventing, capex to keep up with changes. 
         
                  &#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;div&gt;&#xD;
    &lt;br/&gt;&#xD;
  &lt;/div&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/div&gt;</content>
